# v0 POC: AI-Generated Starter Platformer Flow

## Summary
- Bootstrap a new Next.js App Router + TypeScript app in the blank workspace.
- Deliver a two-screen flow: `/` prompt facade -> `/editor` generation experience -> playable starter platformer.
- Use a real OpenAI Responses API call on editor load, but keep the creative input fixed to the internal prompt: `A simple 2D platformer where I control a character that can jump`.
- Show the result as a split-screen editor: read-only AI chat on the left, raw canvas runtime on the right.
- Keep scope intentionally narrow: one starter template, one scene, one player, one ground plane, one follow camera, no persistence.

## Key Changes
- Landing flow
  - Home page is a single large prompt box with a primary CTA.
  - Submitted text is accepted for the ritual of “describe your game,” but v0 explicitly notes that creation currently uses a fixed internal starter prompt.
  - Submit navigates immediately to `/editor`; generation happens there so the user sees the “project is being created” moment.
- Editor flow
  - Editor page renders a restrained two-pane layout with a loading state in the left chat and a canvas placeholder on the right.
  - Once generation completes, the left pane swaps to a seeded transcript and starter summary; the right pane becomes playable.
  - Include a disabled composer or “Follow-up prompts in v1” affordance so the page reads like a real editor, not a static mock.
- AI generation contract
  - Add a server route at `POST /api/starter-project` that calls the OpenAI Responses API with a strict structured-output schema.
  - Default model is `gpt-5.4-mini` via `OPENAI_MODEL`, overridable by env; require `OPENAI_API_KEY`.
  - The API prompt instructs the model to return a starter project pack, not freeform code.
  - The model output is hybrid but bounded: scene data plus behavior descriptors from an allowed enum set. No executable AI-generated JS runs in v0.
  - Validate the response with Zod on the server, retry once on schema failure, and return either a valid project pack or a visible generation error. No silent hardcoded fallback.
- Runtime/canvas
  - Implement a tiny deterministic canvas engine with `requestAnimationFrame`, gravity, horizontal movement, jump, AABB ground collision, and camera X follow clamped to world bounds.
  - Starter art is primitive-only: sky background, rectangle or capsule player, solid ground strip; no asset pipeline.
  - The runtime interprets AI-selected behavior descriptors such as `player_move`, `player_jump`, `gravity`, `solid`, and `camera_follow`.
- Seeded chat
  - The visible user bubble uses the internal starter prompt, so the chat reflects what the AI actually generated from.
  - The AI returns one short creation summary and one short “what exists now” message; the page may prepend one system-style status line like “Generating starter project…”

## Public Interfaces / Types
- `POST /api/starter-project`
  - Request body: optional `{ enteredPrompt?: string }` for analytics/debug only; ignored for generation in v0.
  - Response body: `StarterProjectSpec`.
- `StarterProjectSpec`
  - `project`: `{ name, summary }`
  - `chatTranscript`: array of `{ role: "user" | "assistant", text }`
  - `world`: `{ width, height, gravity, background }`
  - `camera`: `{ mode: "follow_player", targetId, smoothing }`
  - `entities`: array of `{ id, kind: "player" | "ground", x, y, width, height, color, behaviors }`
  - `behaviors`: allowed enum values only; runtime owns the implementation of each behavior.
- `GameState` remains client-side and is derived from `StarterProjectSpec`; it is not persisted or sent back to the server.

## Test Plan
- Flow: submitting from `/` navigates to `/editor`, shows generation state, then resolves into the split layout.
- AI contract: a valid structured response is accepted; an invalid schema triggers one retry and then a visible error state.
- Canvas behavior: the player can move left/right, jump only when grounded, collide with the ground, and remain in camera view while the camera follows.
- UX: the editor remains usable on refresh by regenerating the same starter experience; loading and error states are legible and do not strand the user on a blank screen.
- Regression: no user-entered prompt text accidentally affects generation; only the fixed internal prompt is sent to OpenAI in v0.

## Assumptions
- The blank workspace means we are scaffolding from scratch.
- No auth, database, save/load, version history, asset upload, publishing, or follow-up prompting in this POC.
- Real AI usage is demonstrated through one server-side generation call that assembles the starter project spec; the runtime itself remains deterministic and engine-owned.
- The success bar for v0 is the “magic moment,” not replay variety: one convincingly AI-created starter platformer is enough.


